The innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If one wanted to search for a suitable word that characterizes IBM's strategy most accurately, then this would probably be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, although a century has passed since it was founded.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by their first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
He was already saying that countless global problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became a trademark for the future giant's life (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which was already published by IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen's thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous move towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and did not hesitate to change everything else around.
This allowed us to transform the technologies, the business and also the society in the course of our first century.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director on the occasion of the anniversary.
Thoughtful system
In the 1930s, Watson had been taking care of his employees in a similar way to the entrepreneur Baťa in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid leave as one of the first American employees, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-thought-out pay system for the best newer and merchant.
IBM's long-term relationships with its customers are just as sophisticated.
The company was brilliant in talent promotion right from the start - as one of the first companies in the world IBM abolished all discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan that Palmisan will replace at the head of IBM next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has taken on the position of Sales, Marketing and Strategy Manager.
IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, the company employs almost half a million people.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unwavering position in business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
"From the very beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company," said Economist, the professor of Harvard Business School and the author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
"IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems with the help of technologies," added George Colony of the consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself points out, it is a difference to be present in the market or to form it directly through this presence.
IBM - in the states of its logo called because of family "Big Blue" has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructures, hosting and consultation services in an incredible product width - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM owns the most patents and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most well-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes or diskettes.
With approximately 220 billion dollars of market value (market capitalization), IBM was the second largest technology company this year (right after Apple), with Microsoft being overtaken for the first time since 1996.
Ahead of the Look
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of today's customers - unfortunate for example were the attempt with the own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or also the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on the forward movement, so one must not bind emotionally to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms - and if they don't work, leaving them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM's profits are largely shared by services, software and hardware, each accounting for one fifth.
In 1990 hardware was still the most represented with more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little $15 billion worth of profitable assets, but at the same time invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
In these investments IBM continues after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment in the midst of the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM survives today's crisis without prejudice.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent in rocket form since 2008 and the company's net profit continues to grow.
IBM's corporate slogan is: everything can be changed - only the values can't be changed.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also cope with the next crisis.
IBM history: From cheese cutters to space flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous clocks for the registration of the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the board of directors until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader even overshadowed IBM's founders - Watson's ideas are still based on the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began producing and selling all kinds of machinery for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades of Watson's management of the company, he doubled its turnover to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA conduct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture in 1964 - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came into the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered fully into the business with consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the "Smarter Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, for example to improve the situation in transport and in city management.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932 IBM founded a branch in the then Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at all.
Today IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters is located in Prague and here is also a top research team of world level that deals with voice recognition technology.
