Europe’s most beautiful pools
Jump in the Blue
By Julia Stanek
Paddling pool in Ufo-Optik, pompous pools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience their blue miracle - and after a city tour or a hike the tired legs rest in whirlpool baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past one and a half years, one thing was not to be missed in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Rugging on the water, she looked up into artistically designed domes, she swam towards marble doves waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored art nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she took it up in her notebook - with interesting details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architecture historian Meder in this way - and now presents them in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historical bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland she visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bath culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sports, says Meder - only in the water it is different.
Annoyingly only that swimming fans have to settle for themselves with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can inhale the beguiling scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chirping in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Vienna-based Meder.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splaetzer in the diving pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so big because all the senses are served, said Meder.
And if the builders have tried hard, swimming halls can be a real feast for the eyes: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in baths."
"On the one hand, it is transparent, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format illustrated book "Badefreuden" conveys interesting information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, it found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkali-containing water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: while the Züricher Dachbad has the whole city in mind, one can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which one can observe the hustle and bustle on the ski slope.
The perhaps most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
From three bowls open upwards it steams in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder rose the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell like sulphur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it smells so much like heating oil that one hardly believes to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing medicinal water, which is almost black and whose silt sticks to the skin as soon as you slip into the pelvis - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: When she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder took a look through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds grow between the tiles.
On the other hand, one has counteracted the decay in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already passed through this bath; one can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it was originally from the Black Forest.
"It is already an achievement to merge such different architectural styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only minor.
