21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and disappeared.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture is enthralled by clear forms, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is an apt and famous example of the Brüssler World Exhibition 1958.
At the time, Dicker's pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built Austria's pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like extension in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected in the Swiss Garden near the Vienna South Railway Station after the world exhibition, rebuilt and opened in 1962 a museum of the 20th century - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new house in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Österreichische Galerie Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a remarkable career, among other things, in his youth as an ice figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, implemented the conversion strongly among politicians and monument conservationists, raised public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution then Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at the Technical University of Vienna with Schwanzer and the pavilion was for him a "unfortunately important place" where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original draft, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and ease when it was moved to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far greater problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy throw", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between the house and the street provides for the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection color.
And the cinema room is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that was good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
It had been difficult with the pavilion "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because an urban development lucky case has occurred: Around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another case of luck may still occur: The 21er Haus could be strengthened by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss Garden.
