And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied during his second term at the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers have given their students the exam answers so that they themselves were well-advised in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that every day we lie between 10 and 200 times.
Many of these lies, however, are regarded as a lie of necessity.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or "uncovering lies" is one that is important for each person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Scharaden, in which the goal is to call "Have You!", the defiling of a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out extensive research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush and do not always blush.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to expose and expose.
A trained lie-masker can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing area of exposure. And it is clear that defiling a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiating or managing is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, raising their interest and mastering their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people that men are more often "self-directed" lies than women whose lies are more "orienting" - usually protecting the feelings of others - that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First of all, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "Baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent assessment of changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should better know when someone usually always jumps with the foot, so they don't blame him wrongly when he jumps with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not evidence of exposure.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questioners often falsely signal that an interview is over just to look for this relaxation after the interview.
Also, watch your subject's language.
Scott Peterson's slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving persons can also use a distanced language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if one repeats a tricky question in the whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than objective, which often makes the alarm bells shrill.
There's no magic to expose lies, but you can learn skills that allow you to unmask them.
These skills make it easier for anyone to become a victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
