Climatic adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of the change and fuelled great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of the climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year.This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, with 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa having no employment, equivalent to 4.53 per cent of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that the politics of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing at the moment is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, liquidity losses in the market due to the cuts in funds by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are illegally accumulating dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased, due on the one hand to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here looking for work here, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account. According to INEGI, this includes 60.38 percent of the employees in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are accompanied by low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to the reduction in economic activity and rising unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (National Economic Authority), the ADI was $630,597 from January to June, a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143,312 dollars in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) for its part recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debts
In view of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The State Congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the country’s economic sectors could be identified by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the entrepreneurship the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's incapacity for government obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa has been really poor this year, and hard work needs to be done to regain the terrain lost this year and we need to make a double effort in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy that is not sufficiently moving to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining appointments
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, said that it was necessary to encourage the state to become more dynamic productive.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
