The court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The transition of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional actions filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, and by virtue of which the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be brought forward due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the legislative decree detailing the switchover to terrestrial digital television.
This resolution rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the case brought by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed that the Decree-Law be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the Decree-Law would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and the legal requirements.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. After the lawsuits were accepted, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to establish the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take under general rules.
"I also do not believe that if this were done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because the central government is responsible for state affairs.
Replacing analogue signals with digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it makes better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the exploitation of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, "because it included economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "needed the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of characteristics that put the constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital transition, through the government, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It could not be concluded that the government would intervene in the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree, since the laws adopted by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballot papers individually in Michoacán is being considered
