The possibility of counting the ballots individually this year is a reality at the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governorial elections is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this spirit, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th the polling post had adopted a series of regulations to harmonise local regulations with state reforms in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, electoral law, or electoral justice law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the time limits set for this, arguing that he had no objection to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and judged the State Commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", as he did not have the right to "decide or veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, explained that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority can count the ballots in part or in full.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available on file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the complete ballot certificates may be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the second-place winner, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that an explicit application is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages subject to a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is just under 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
