Monti said he would present the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of government to the President.
"I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," said the former EU Commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well-stacked," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal. Meanwhile, Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has brought the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package that was called for by Europolitics in order to regain the weak confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti to press ahead has been exacerbated by the fluctuating market situation, which has led to the interest burden on Italian government bonds for 10 years at a rate of 7 per cent, which is the level at which Greece and Ireland have been forced to apply for the European bailout.
