At 3:30 p.m., the police approached Montral No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people entering the building.
The four were arrested immediately.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The urban tender for the 16 gates opens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona anew.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its defamation on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
He was even compared in numbers with New York Central Park.
With the fall of the CMB in 1987, the park became the upper limit of Barcelona again in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in the north-south direction, but up (mountains) and down (sea).
Collserolas as a natural park plays with this idea.
The role model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
This was the time when the city issued a huge invitation to tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access gates to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that's the way it is, or someone's planning to put gates in the country.
The question arises by itself: Collserola, Park or Berg?
The call is not only from an organisational point of view, but also in view of a reflection on the city the topic of discussion in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona.
It is already almost a recurring topic, which two members of this old settled caste, who meet in the elevator, can fall back on.
And that is exactly the fact that offers the material for one of the rare similarities between what three architects from Barcelona think about it and some university professors who applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, it is "necessary" to speak about the "front of the mountain" after the attack on the coast, as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, the one about the green apples, has not been conducted.
"One should assume the principle that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect, for whom the title "Tore of Collserola" contains a "lexical trap": it must not be imagined as "access to a park, but as a limitation of areas in which action must be taken."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in urban planning, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Risks arising from the "uncertainty that the design of a public space today entails" after the experience of the 1980s, who had their "swan song" in the field of the forum.
The first fear is one's own limitation to what can be built up.
"Limiting something always means setting the next step", i.e. crossing it.
"You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the present [referring to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM)] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who adheres more closely to the question, says that the side of Collserola, which goes towards Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that does not go towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola, which should not "fall on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration that it has given its committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
He also notes that the proximity of the mountains to the city is the escort letter, which allows architects to take part in the debate, although he expresses his "doubt" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("just the right thing," he says) "We architects should only be a tool."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, since in the terms of the tender a global view of Collserola is missing: "There were 16 competitions in the cross-section," he says, "on the axis of the mountain-sea. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area in its entirety."
This has led, at least in his case, to his participation in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip is equipped directly above the Ronda de Dalt in its entire length, which creates a soft transition between town and green areas.
