Thus was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopeist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November 4th, a Lophoscopeist from the Criminal Investigation Unit (CTI) from Cali, who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia), admitted: "Alfonso Cano" by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopeists in the CTI department, Eliazar González was on standby this week, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the attack against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big awaited him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of the men who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world could be. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his actual name).
However, when he reached with the examiner the place where the body was located, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because this was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, wore no glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant ladle and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the print sheet.
He had seen it right: It was Alfonso Cano.
The same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for Traces
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the tribute given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
The dactyloscopy is an exact science without error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopeists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders submit false identification papers or have none.
We'll take their fingerprints and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house during a theft, because the thief had supported himself with his hand right here when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we could take the print of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspect, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, he is nevertheless associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A Dactyloscopician of the CTI explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents are taken from the object."
When they appear, a plant ladle or band is used to take them with you.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the civil status office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers," explained the expert from the CTI.
He said that not everything was as depicted in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
