Austria
Entry of a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution
The government of the large Social Democratic/Christian Democratic coalition in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also avoid any degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top credit rating (AAA).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann who had announced this decision of the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the Austrian public debt is at 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had not fallen to AA+, we would have to pay an additional three billion euros each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice-Chancellor and Christian Democratic Foreign Minister.
Austria also makes a request at the Brussels summit of the euro area Member States on 26 October: the Heads of State or Government would have called for the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 as well as a return to the public balance of accounts in the Constitution or by adopting an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government for this purpose is similar to the "German model" since Germany had been the first European country to have incorporated such a "rule" into the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017, the state's structural budget deficit should not exceed the 0.35% limit of GDP, whereas regional states and municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The objective is to eliminate budgetary debt under the 60% criterion established by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
