Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
Availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to have an election meeting to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, an enormous proportion of the world's population should not have to renounce a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity constantly, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to forego nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source for substitution, nor in Switzerland, which just intends to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
The UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States has decided to add another unit to their park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant, which was closed after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is oriented towards renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The Berlin election will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, in particular on Russia, due to increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for reflection.
Denmark is, on the one hand, the European leader in wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, and, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key element of competitiveness and a guarantee of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a strong increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay, as it shows resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us bear in mind that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a plethora of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France decided to withdraw from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual EUR 6 billion in exports of capital goods and nuclear energy would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of his producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is no more a miracle tool for generating electricity than a devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks on existing plants, such as at the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the safety concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, without consequences for man and the environment.
At Chernobyl, the drama was provoked by reactor construction and infinite human error.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented proportions that caused the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the previous two.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a design that enables it to resist such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power itself.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party leaders dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overload of police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students by the authorities had shaped the weekly shows, the Interior Minister had casually (see Libération of 23 May) announced that France "had no need for talent, bricklayers or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right hand side, the tone of Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including more than 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left hand side by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that "France cannot absorb all the world's poverty".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both right and left.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to the immigrants.
Francois Hollande confines himself in his programme to banalities, which point out that development in partnership allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may affect the elections, but it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present to us in a recent work summarising the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Limiting immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace the local workers, especially the less skilled ones, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage-earners, since they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors which are unencumbered in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that are not attractive to local wage earners, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where education is not aligned with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also brings about a positive effect of immigration migration on wages and the domestic labour market.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in an inclusive, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants and economic growth is beneficial (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, on average around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person immigrating to Germany at the age of 30 will, on average, contribute a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth".
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a sensitive asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had let the entire 20th century pass over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece.
Some had believed that it was enough to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy triumph over its enemies once and for all.
One knows since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a characteristic of the mental attitude.
The general right to vote, which is the necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can become just as well an "oppression instrument", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot expressed it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, education, economic and social community spirit, jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe in which we find ourselves is an economic crisis, but it is just as serious and first and foremost a political and democratic crisis.
The change of attitude of the Greek True-False referendum would have had a double enlightening character in this respect: one that of the need for a powerful return of politics, on the other hand, but also that of the disturbing feeling of their impossibility, of their inappropriateness.
