Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glory and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level, last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned the valve control, which transports the Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length that connects the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of building a third line sound on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is now more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Nord-Stream pipeline with a "new German-Andean pact" linked to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically very sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of a reduction in European energy, as the project has made a break between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes had little desire to see a Russian state company permanently settling at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than one minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is not considered likely by the designers, since the welds were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing ship and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one metre, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily guaranteed by pressure.
This amounts to 200 bar at the entrance point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have combined their forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a corporate group called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company under a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the volume of gas transported will be," Jens Müller explained.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are prepared to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline is exposed on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic metres of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Launched by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, by candlelight with the hours spent writing.
The notebook of Moleskine is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular cover, its rubber band, the eggshell sides, as over time aged.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as it is known today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's specialist consultant at the time, is commissioned with the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton rack, which is used, for example, for upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travellers.
"Moleskine revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was regarded as an icon of avant-garde artists," explains Maria Sebregondi, now a brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established itself with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early days, now employs over 100 people and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centres and is committed to asserting its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which exist despite the upswing of e-mails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the Moleskine company: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour" in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, at the Locarno Film Festival, the company also launched a cover with leopard patterns.
Moleskine profited from its success and cultural zeitgeist and managed to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer covers... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that brings envy to the plan: In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought up by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in the history of the Moleskine company.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice the average: 19% against 9% unemployment of the total population.
Disheartening?
"No, according to Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "Week of Work for the Disabled".
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
It is more common for older people: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them have no Abitur and only 10,000 disabled people are among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled, compared with 38% of the total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the labour market and make it "the core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the attitudes that are certainly but slowly evolving.
A study carried out in April by the Association IMS-Entreprendre for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge regarding disabled people", which was "overrepresented" by "persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually deprived persons".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, General Director of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that are not respecting this law.
Proof: The number of "paying" establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the paid-up amounts between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which provides for increases in contributions, put a lot of pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc said.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while enterprises with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
